log: Find the distribution of customers based on how many orders they have placed. Include customers with zero orders. Ignore any orders whose comment contains the substring ‘special’ followed by ‘requests’. Count how many customers fall into each order-count group and output the number of customers per group. Sort by most orders. Output in textfile.

title: Agent: SpecifierAgent Output
log: Using the customers and orders datasets/tables, produce a distribution of customers by how many orders each customer has placed, including customers with zero orders. Exclude any individual order whose comment contains the substring "special" followed by "requests" (i.e., ignore orders where the comment contains the phrase "special requests"). For each customer, count their qualifying orders; then group customers by that order count and count how many customers fall into each group. Output the result as a two-column list (order_count, customer_count), sorted by order_count descending (most orders first). Write the final output to a text file.

log.thoughts: The request needs customer data and order data (including order comments) to count orders per customer, exclude orders whose comment contains the substring 'special' followed by 'requests', and include customers with zero orders. Therefore I selected the 'customers' and 'orders' tables. No external text files are required.

steps.detailed_description: Load the orders table (columns used: o_orderkey, o_custkey, o_comment) and the customers table (primary key column: c_custkey) as the two input datasets. These are two separate input operators producing the raw orders and raw customers relations.

On the orders relation: filter out any order whose o_comment contains the substring 'special requests' (case-sensitive match of the phrase). From the remaining orders, compute for each customer (group by o_custkey) the number of qualifying orders and produce a relation with schema (c_custkey, order_count). This step outputs per-customer order counts for customers who have at least one qualifying order.

Left-join the customers relation (customers.c_custkey) with the per-customer order counts relation (from step 2) on customers.c_custkey = order_counts.c_custkey to ensure customers with zero qualifying orders are included. For customers without a matching order_count, set order_count = 0. Output relation schema: (c_custkey, order_count).

Group the customer-level relation by order_count and compute for each order_count the number of customers having that count. Produce a relation with two columns (order_count, customer_count). Then sort this relation by order_count descending (largest order_count first).
Write the final two-column sorted result (order_count, customer_count) to the requested text file (one row per group, formatted as two columns).

log.thoughts: Load both tables, filter and count qualifying orders per customer, left-join to include customers with zero orders, then aggregate by order_count and sort before writing to file. This gives a small, clear DAG of input → filter+count → join → aggregate+sort → output.
